The first virtual provider is already coming to Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe he won't be waiting long.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz on the fact that the Czech mobile operators work at all to the most expensive in Europe.
Incidentally, this was confirmed by the ČTÚ Telecommunications Authority, which pointed out that the price for a text message here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the last steps of the European Commission in regulating roaming charges, there is likely to be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile phone providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a fight.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of well over 100 %.
Mobile providers, on the other hand, like to scoff at the fact that there is an extremely high level of competition in the Czech market.
The chairman of the Czech Telecommunications Authority Council (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who had often stated in the past that there was no room for any other provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has much chance (by the way, it would probably hardly find any frequencies).
But there is still one possibility - a virtual provider.
The entry of virtual providers into the mobile market led to a significant price reduction, which the classic mobile operators had to react to.
Before such companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, there were voices similar to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, one does not have to look for examples for long.
In February we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus rise to the country's fifth largest provider.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers are usually seen as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to put on a non-scrupulous target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and trust," says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar approach could be adopted in the Czech Republic as in Poland.
The press spokesperson of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer."
In the Czech Republic, mobile phone providers say no chance
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile phone provider Czech Republic conquers, this will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look particularly hopeful.
Mobilking will enter the market in other countries of our region," says a phone call for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press spokesperson of the financial group Penta.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything in their power not to create a potential competitor.
Their interest in starting a virtual mobile phone provider has long shown the group GTS Novera, who wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the area of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile providers.
With some of them, we have already been able to achieve negotiations," said the press spokesperson of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
Maybe we'll have better times now.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a fully-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has a high degree of specificity vis-à-vis other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the Telefónica O2 press department.
Other suppliers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
The press spokesperson from T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: "So far we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build further."
And she adds: "T-Mobile's network will hardly show up as a virtual provider until the end of the year.
At this moment, we would already have to have a concrete offer to be able to think so in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we regard as the best from the point of view of customers.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is the search for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the suppliers
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider called more competition, this would lead to lower prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that suppliers can draw on a strand when it comes to something also demonstrates the long time to come about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ came from the company T-Mobile at the time when U:fon came into the market.
This is also evidence of the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is right as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently also been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
In view of this approach of mobile operators, however, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is astounded.
This is not just the attitude of ČTÚ, which, unfortunately - unlike the UK and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
The latter shall have sole responsibility for the protection of economic competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem his very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider through the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic suppliers," says Kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS in his reply to our request.
Such a formulation would not surprise representatives of the suppliers.
This is more than questionable by an authority representing consumer interests and, inter alia, by ensuring that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, if Kristian Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be seen that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a fall in prices are probably not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, it is really shocking to note that the three mobile operators are almost already in a state of harmony, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it really is just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same petrol price at the gas stations is certainly just coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any evidence of anti-competitive action in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so it does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for its market action.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are probably also missing from the regulatory authority for telecommunications," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications from the point of view of economic competition is a single market.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the agreement of the network operator is always necessary for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And the mobile provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not agree with this argument, it should be at least a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting in a similar way.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when negotiating with all suppliers.
In the telecommunications services, the shift of responsibility to the ČTÚ is a rather common trick, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole issue.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of ČTÚ's competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications has not succeeded, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS only have to know this too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's all right when no one's looking.
First of all, the functioning of any pseudovirtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
It is companies which issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
Usually they are companies operating in the field of multi-level marketing.
Own mobile phone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies are usually only available to selected ones.
The joke is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar type of resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a breach of the contractual conditions with which we will then deal, which may lead to the termination of cooperation with the relevant society," answered Martina Kemrov to our question on this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not go hand in hand with the controllers of mobile telephony providers.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned above, they can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such action.
In fact, from the activities of these companies, profits are not too negligible, and at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čpický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows for such kinds of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot fully possess it like the normal customers of the mobile phone providers."
This alone, however, the ČTÚ should at least seem strange.
In addition, another question opens up for the ÚOHS.
Before such action, mobile operators close their eyes, why do they block themselves against a virtual provider?
It is to be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to discover such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration of the providers, they do not know any of them and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As already stressed several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers brought with it a significant price decrease in the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have developed, the classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence virtually more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - too small or too saturated a market, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies in these moments intervened, which did not in any way seek to safeguard the interests of mobile operators but of their customers.
If it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this was followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing themselves all over the place like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot lose the impression that in these cases ambiguity in the competences is more than favorable.
But let's not throw the flint in the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon be resuming.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
