The Prague transport companies will also transport a chip on Wednesday for the first time.
Wednesday, 1 October 2008, will enter the history of Prague's transport operations as a date on which the first passengers will enter a subway, tram or bus, carrying an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
These can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously play it on their smart card, in the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the underground stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zhrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons have also been available on the website of the transport companies www.dpp.cz since yesterday.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon.
Those who use Internet sales can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they have had to wait regularly for their paper tickets in long queues.
You buy the coupon on the Internet, it is played on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these places there is also a switch with trained staff at your disposal, which advises interested parties when buying the Internet and also plays the coupon on the map," says the speaker of the Martin Opatrný project.
In addition to the libraries, you can also play the electronic coupons on self-service vending machines on the Opencard, which are installed in some metro-vestibüls.
What do such vending machines look like?
They are red, reminding of driver's license devaluers, the passengers may have noticed them already in the subway stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but until the end of the year it should be eighty," Opatrný adds.
The coupon controls a machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines that will work from tomorrow is easy.
All you have to do is insert the chip card, and the previously acquired coupon is self-playing.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburbs and on the bus lines with numbers 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants in particular from the municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia reach the capital.
"In the trains that are part of Prague's integrated traffic, the train attendants have reading devices that allow them to check the validity of the coupons according to time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the organisation Robid. This organisation is responsible for preparing the timetables for Prague's transport operations.
The suburban buses have card readers at the driver's checkout.
When entering, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the open card must be placed at a marked point on the side of the checkout.
The driver thus controls the validity of the played coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the played coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information," says Drápal.
A passenger who does not drive by suburban buses and who does not know when the validity of the coupon ends can go to the self-service machines where the coupons are played on the card.
Here the information about the validity of his documents is displayed on the display of the device.
