Isabel Bayón calls back the memory of the dancer from Seville Tórtola Valencia
A flamenco dancer from Seville worships a dancer who also comes from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Catalane (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and the mother Andalusian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in the Triana district and when she was three years old, her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and an expert for oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first fighters for the emancipation of women, such as Isadora Ducan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, a vegetarian, and stood for the abolition of the corset, which restricted free female movement.
Isabel Bayón was fascinated by the life of this woman, who left her traces of the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe between the wars.
`I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested to me this role which seemed impossible to me.'
'We don't try to tell about her life without keeping her Esprit,' said the flamenco dancer.
Your dance grounds helped me a lot in Flamenco.
'The dance of the butterfly' seemed to me, for example, like Guajira, or 'the dance of the snake' like Tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I have been told that my dancing is also in this aesthetic area,' she claims.
The production is based on two extraordinary collaborations: with Miguel Poveda, who will sing for Isabel again at one of her performances, as he did in `La puerto aberta'; and with Flamenco master Matilde Coral, who wanted to work exceptionally with one of her ex-students.
`Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work, and I feel very honored.'
The production also includes musical composition and guitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, with the vocals of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; with the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with the actor Juanfra Jjarez, he takes on the role of companion of the artists who were Divas in whom he is in love again and again.'
This work also tells in a certain way of the life of this woman, who was known in as far places as India, the United States or Russia and also throughout Europe, although she lived in London normally.
`I wanted to call her back in memory, because I think she is one of the women who have a tremendous influence on a particular era and whose works no longer have any value today and therefore she knows even less', says Bayón.
The performance takes place today at 20:30 in the Theater Lope de Vega.
