The drivers, who can be receded due to the alcohol level, will have to install the `Alcolock'.
The authority orders that the driver, who had three official penalties for the alcohol level, install this system in his car, which forbids him to start the car in a drunken state. If he is alcoholic, then the car does not start.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the General Public Prosecutor's Office's report. According to their information, it is a pilot project that will last for a year.
The purpose is to re-socialise the driver, which is why he is given a course for the re-education of traffic behaviour.
The Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for the Safety of Automobiles will also participate in this, as experienced by the Attorney General.
According to statistics, between 30-75% of drivers who were shown more than once because of driving under the influence of alcohol were taxed again.
The `alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents the start of the car when the driver has tested alcohol; or if an alcohol concentration is detected which is higher than permitted.
It costs more than 1 000 euros, the costs are borne by the person who imposes the penalty.
In this context, a study carried out in the US in 2007 showed that these devices already prevent cars equipped in the first year after their introduction up to 65% of the violations of the rules.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved every year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to tackle this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate their implementation, a legal reform can be implemented in the ordinary way, and yet a reform of the basic law is required which is necessary for the law enforcement process.
The device is still available on the Spanish markets, in no business, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
Tomorrow, the House of Representatives will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses, which has already been done in France.
