Discussion - From the blood that has become safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of her founding yesterday, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, which was severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, during the 1980s, the national blood reserves managed by the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross were contaminated with HI virus and hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and public dissatisfaction, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever aimed at bringing light to the circumstances which had led to such a tragedy and to developing guidelines to prevent a further disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to report, several provinces then set up a committee to develop a new system of blood canning in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, who is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started her work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood-preserved system in Quebec, remembers Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood canning and through the work in this area during the following years, we have regained public confidence', she says, before they proudly emphasize that by the beginning of 2008 almost 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted on the principle of caution.
At that time, we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of cattle madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
`And we had no idea whether this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of the reports by Krever and Gélineau, which states that exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as it is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
Thus, in April 1999, no blood was taken from persons who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was being transmitted over the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we used has quite a meaning.
In 1999 a much more accurate HIV detection technique appeared on the market: the Nucleic Acid Tests (NST) which allow the donor to detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation period between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not see it, was greatly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
In other words, 12 million canned blood would have to be distributed before someone was infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood canned every year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV being transfused via a blood canned.
I believe that today you can feel well when you get or write a blood transfusion to restore your health,' says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can enter the system.
Only last year did the Chikungunya virus appear on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects over the blood.
We need to monitor continuously', Dr. Décary continues before she emphasizes that Hema-Quebec must also provide sufficient supply in addition to a secure supply.
'The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
Since anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood supply network, which on average accounts for only 3% of Quebec's eligible residents.
In doing so, any healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who make their blood available are not accepted because they have, for example, AIDS or malaria, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from blood donation for a year.
With this 3%, we are able to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and donate no more blood.
It's hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to keep them and make them become regular donors.
Life today is so hectic that you rarely find the time to spend an hour on blood donation,' laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Hema-Quebec provides not only blood preserves but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which are used almost exclusively in case of severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, there is a rich blood cell that can help treat severe diseases, such as leukemia.
`A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to decrease more than a thousand annually.
`We should probably start by making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year', Dr. Décary continues, who describes this program of umbilical cord loss as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all the hospitals in Quebec.
