The psychology of oversupply - or why we are willing to pay more
When auctioning, the buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bid.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have now been able to discover the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to get beat in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore ready to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play Lotto while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were investigated by functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured at the losses of the auction, where oversupply of the opponent plays an important role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-remuneration" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore considered that the price increase could be explained by the avoidance of an over-reaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also commissioned investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should participate against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their operations.
Another group was also promised 15 dollar reward, in case they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was that the emphasis on the one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypotheses expressed by neurologists, the members of the "against losing" group were prepared for higher stakes than those in the control or "winning" group.
"These results can not be derived from previous economic theory.
In fact, the behaviour observed at auctions has so far been based only on the joy of winning, or on the avoidance of risk.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so that we now have a third explanation prepared" - said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should the doctor visit?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of people infected is estimated to be one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for various viruses caused by infectious liver disease.
Symptoms are often similar - inflammation of the liver and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogens, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, sheath secret or saliva).
Travelers are recommended to vaccinate against the viruses A and B at any rate, there is no vaccine against the virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are seen approximately two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
Afterwards, yellow fever occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery can last up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die every year from the far more serious diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every tenth infected person is in medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated may lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease, as the pathogen will negate the liver cells in an insidious way - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular monitoring, is essential.
There are three groups where this disease is more common: those who have undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the general practitioner at the first signs of unknown origin.
In time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, which bans the risk of infection and prevents the development of cancer.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, 2004 organized for the first time by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, their emergence and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
As recent research shows, religious faith acts like a kind of "pain" that has already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Researchers at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment: It has been investigated to what extent belief in God influences human pain, reported the British newspaper "Telegraph".
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the faithful were able to eliminate most of the pain.
Through a brain scan technology, it could even be demonstrated that the Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain regulation.
The study was the first in a research project in which scientists also participate philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university.
During the experiment, a sparkling device was attached to the left hand to the subjects, which the electric shocks gave off.
The participants were asked to concentrate heavily on two paintings: on the one hand, a picture of the mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other, Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the vision of the Virgin Mary would create a kind of religious trance among the faithful, while they chose da Vinci's image, because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt as soothing.
The subjects each spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they should either look at the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that at the sight of the Mother of God, they felt "in security" as if they were "careful" and felt "peace and quiet".
As they looked at the religious painting, they reported over 12% less pain than if they had Leonardo's work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, said that similar effects could also be produced with other, strongly-performing images also among the atheists, one would just have to find the corresponding photo.
"We need to find an image that triggers very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father," says the psychologist.
The Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practice of faith should change our personality, and in many cases, too," says Wright.
According to these excellent results, only the question remains as to what effect a Madonna image of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
