Intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new accident prevention technologies if not to imitate natural obstacle sensors?
For example, those of the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented in which the Nissan engineers of Hummeln were inspired by the creation of new accident prevention systems.
In cooperation with the Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system controlled by autobots, a mini-car, equipped with the properties of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, Product Manager for Technology PR and Research Development at the exhibition.
The compound eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles to the BR23C in a field of vision of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates its distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of seconds, and the author immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place instinctively.
"If this were not the case, the Autobot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the Autobot Project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered unavoidable.
The entire process must reflect the behavior of bees when they divert other bees.
And that has to run in a fraction of a second.
However, unlike the bees, the deviation can not go up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, only in the direction of the reversibility of the tyres.
While the bees here are endlessly open to avoid other bees, the researchers at the author robot could only use the rotational movement, or acceleration and braking.
The BR23C contains lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy-efficient and therefore have a longer life span than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it comes to the instinctive, intelligent response, and less to the processing of the data, and even less to the ability to store it.
This device only has to process some inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It does not have to store it, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction using previous manoeuvres, so that it constantly only takes a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabytes and megabytes of heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately guiding the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the goal.
