Napolitano: "Prevention of accidents at work is crucial"
Every day in Italy 2500 accidents at work, three people die and 27 remain disabled for life.
For 2007, the data from Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were about 1200.
These figures prove the seriousness of a phenomenon which causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) in all provinces of Italy will be celebrating the 58th National Day for Victims of Accidents at Work to draw the attention of the social institutions and the media to this dramatic situation.
"The alarming data spread by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention at work is.", the President of the Republic of Giorgio Napolitano confirms in his communication to the President of Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The Head of State expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to the prevention of jobs, the protection of the injured workers, the support of the families of the victims and the awareness of public opinion".
"An outraged "basta" has risen to this point; understandably in the case of tragedies which, in terms of their size, trigger some vortex in the media and public participation. However, everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events that can even be repeated in their own dynamics."
Napolitano does not hide that "there is in any case also a resource problem: it must be invested decisively in education and information."
A special importance is attached to the numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness-raising within the school framework of young people who feed on the world of work.
It is our duty to focus attention on this phenomenon and not to divert attention from its social seriousness.
On the other hand, the President of the Chamber of Gianfranco Fini stressed "how the phenomenon of job-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency, which offends the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work on decisive rules that aim to put an end to the problem".
"The data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight improvement, but this does not exclude that the number of deaths caused by work is far too high," stresses President of Anmil, Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this "positive tendency" to mean less attention. That's exactly what causes the tragedy in the end."
"How do you think that you are doing too little to counter the phenomenon of accidents? You can fight against it through various actions.
In our opinion, stronger controls and inspections are necessary – according to Mercandelli; but also stronger measures to educate workers who are already starting school."
"An additional effort is necessary - he adds - in terms of communication and awareness-raising of public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers is in demand of a phenomenon which constitutes a social emergency".
Mercandelli also referred to "the progressive deterioration in the protection of victims of accidents at work" and denounced the "disposal of the social system against which we are fighting in recent years".
"The aim is therefore to return a guarantee to the employee on insurance so that the fate of the victim of an accident at work does not depend on voluntary or incidental donations that are decided upon by a legislator at the time".
Mp3 player under charge: danger of hearing damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as Mp3 players, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
This is reported by the European Commission, which cites the opinion of the Csrseri (Scientific Committee on the current and recently identified health risks) of the EU in a report published in Brussels today.
"The report – as it says in a comment – makes it clear that 5-10% of those who hear loud music with portable music for at least five years per day for more than one hour per day risk the permanent loss of their hearing".
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people, who usually put portable music devices and mobile phones on a high volume, are irrevocably damaging their hearing without knowing it," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific findings – it is said by the EU – there is a clear risk that is pressing for rapid action.
What really matters is to raise consumer awareness and make this information a common good.
In the light of these scientific findings, we need to re-examine the existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology".
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music devices among young people.
"Scientists - as the EU Communication concludes - confirm that there is a good deal of concern and that the European Commission, together with the other members of the European Union and those concerned, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise that comes from portable music and similar devices."
There is already a European standard at the moment which limits the level of noise from portable music devices to 100 dB. Concern about the damage that could result from an excessive noise load.
It is very possible to limit these damage to solutions such as the reduction of volume and the length of noise emission.
In their report, the European Scientific Committee points out that if users of portable music devices only hear five hours a week (only more than 89 decibels) of music, then the legal boundaries that apply to the maximum noise level at the workplace are already exceeded.
Those who cross this line risk the complete loss of hearing within five years.
This represents 5-10% of the users of such devices, whose number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
