The Elite is in danger
The phenomenon had already been revealed a few days ago when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the 700 billion-dollar budget of the White House: a large part of the Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This confirms yesterday's issue of the New York Times, which reports on how the crisis in the run-up to the Republican Party is becoming more and more divided into its old and moderate East Coast Souls, which always favored the state institutions and the business community and that neoconservative who are hostile to "the one in Washington" and the financial world and, above all, in the south and the centre of states voters.
This part of the party owes its rise, above all, to the voice of what I mentioned above.
This example just mentioned is, however, only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake announces or even already represents: not only in the United States, but also in the whole of the West, and perhaps beyond that, will be affected by these.
Both in the Member States and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long-afraid events, which finally take shape and come to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the discovery of the unprecedented Renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis is a decline in banking and financial institutions, which have close links with abroad and at the same time manage an enormous amount of private household assets living in a single state.
This means an immediate political problem for governments: how to deal with the families concerned, which is also a huge mass of voters.
The crisis therefore appears economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have gone far beyond itself and lost its right to speak: the clear evidence of this has been given by the EU, which, due to its division into various national and international conflicts, cannot find a common way.
Therefore, everyone is now counting on the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and, above all, the distribution of aid funds: since the crisis has become increasingly serious, only the US is in the economic situation to save itself without foreign aid.
In addition to the funds, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus, two conditions that cannot be overvalued – under certain circumstances – on which otherwise probably no international organisation and no market will be able to resort in a similar way.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed on the state-national element is in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance that is most recently associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically it is right now, when we were so convinced that we have long since entered a networked total empire, into a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, of intangibles, that we must suddenly see how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvests and oil.
While they can all be transported from one place to the other of the world, they are still extremely connected to a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such a territory is in favour of another who lives in a yieldless, waterless or oil-free area.
I now come to the second innovation, which, however, requires a short introduction.
Anyone who says territory, who says government, who says politics, says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leaderships, so the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of disillusionment over the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy, which have emerged as insufficient and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and more disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, an inadequacy, an image of inefficiency, a feeling of distance, all of which is directed towards an entire class of managers of the Western countries.
It seems that the conviction among many parts of the population is the way forward, that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their Way of Life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content is the majority as ever alien and more common.
The demand for leadership thus nourishes underground a weak but powerful movement of the demise of the leading class and the traditional political establishment. This manifests itself in unexpected "revolts" of the voters and in the immediate reversal of the collective state of mind of the recent times: starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, through the collapse of the Labour Party in the UK, to the rebellion of American MEPs against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value of what is happening in the lower social strata of the West these days, and even stronger from the financial crisis and driven to overdimensionality.
In view of all of this, it would simply be exaggerated to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
