Medicines: never take fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed due to their refreshing quality and their vitamin richness, especially in summer, can cause serious health damage if they are taken at the same time with certain vital medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on their absorption by the body.
David Bailey, professor of the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points out the risk of packaging and fresh fruit juices in connection with medication. During the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again called for an alarm: it is enough for a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital medicines so that they are practically eliminated and thus endanger the health of the patients.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some medicines such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovasculars, anxiolytics and neurologicals, up to toxic levels.
MEDICINAL PRODUCTS – In a report two years ago, the same Agency had warned doctors and patients about the dangers of this mixture, stressing that what is being drunk in combination with medicines such as diazepan or methadone.
IT IS NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT – According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active substances inhibited by the fruit juices is long.
The appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the Università Statale di Milano: "These results are usually passed on immediately to the various international manufacturers, who are thus free to change the consumer information.
It is therefore advisable to read the package leaflet at all times and, if there is any confusion, not to ask a pharmacist or a doctor," stresses the expert of the Ansa Agency.
