Open Office, it appears the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package
The day of publication of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the Open Source software gains an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in the public administration, as a free replacement for Microsoft's Office.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers, which is monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is now presenting itself to the public with some new features: in addition to a revised and now more sparsely designed start menu, it has now finally reached a level of compatibility with Apple's Mac OS x operating system, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, the latest standard ISO version.
Eight against was also on compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
