The program is also available for the Linux operating system except for Windows and Mac OS.
On request, the installation CD can be sent to your home or office.
However, if freedom of charge can be an incentive for the distribution of the program in private households, it is also in the business area where OpenOffice could succeed the big throw: finally, various public administration and schools have already moved to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of a training offer, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opening up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word equivalent text creation program; Calc, the table program that aims to displace Excel; Impress, to create presentations like with PowerPoint; Dbase to operate databases instead of the more familiar access; and lastly Draw, a graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to achieve 5 million downloads – a goal that can be easily exceeded at already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
