Students Victims of up to 900 Euro per room rental prices
The market for apartments for students does not know any crises.
According to the latest study of the Sunia, the tenant union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on very serious trains. A whole group of students lose their right to study as effectively as their families are unable to support them at this level" – according to the Sunia, Laura Mariani, "in these cities the great demand of the students leads to a deformation of the market that has also damaged the other residents.
In addition, most rental offers include a number of infringements: free contracts, missing registrations, without a rental price limit, unauthorized sub-rents.
For the Sunia there is the need for exceptional measures, which result in a revision of taxation at lower rental prices.
It turns out that in Milan a sleeping space is needed in the Brianza district of about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Nere district) and ends with 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera district or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, an average sleeping space costs 350/400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the neighborhoods around the university, 250/280 euros are for a sleeping area of needs, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, the prices in the neighborhoods around the university are about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a sleeping area in a double room.
Only a little deeper are the rents in the districts around the other universities of Rome: 550 euros in Ostienne and Cinecittà.
Only those who choose outside districts can save money: 300 Euros for a sleeping area and 450 Euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples you will need 300-450 euros for a sleeping area, for a room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive districts, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari a sleeping area costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they have a higher weight in the urban economy.
In the cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more common, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: a rental that is 25-30% above the average is required by foreign students.
Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinema halls
The historical cinemas close due to the favored multiplex cinemas.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture by director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening at the moment in the large urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of the cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, means in the long term death for the one-room cinema in the centre. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the trains of a cultural crime.
The most affected are historical places full of memories, "It is like losing a friend with whom one has travelled a piece of street full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oskar and the great prize of Cannes 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a well-forgotten cinema world.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years the vast amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these coins mostly paid the cinemas in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are the Emilia Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This testifies to the fact that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years Lombardy has led the lists, 81 are both in Tuscany and in Emilia Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," said Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but first and foremost the maintenance of the already existing one, because closing a hall in the city, not all its regular customers are willing to visit instead of the old one a multiplex cinema in the periphery.
And here remains the missing budget for the fund of the trade association outside of consideration: the debt burden recorded by the state amounts to approximately EUR 10 million.
It is a disgrace from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros would be needed in the year".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, because of the fears about the old cinema halls, has decided to protect it through an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of this kind in Italy, which aims to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
The measures envisaged include tax advantages for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be possible to drive into the traffic-limited areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking rates.
"It is a pleasant initiative," said Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also design new concepts.
But we certainly also need a better audio and video equipment to be able to align something against the superpower of the multiplex rooms, because finally the audience of today is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of Baghiera's "Supercinema", the place of my childhood and youth, was the crucial point that led me to start the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the idea for 10 years.
For 25 years I have been living in Rome; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side to avoid seeing the dust-covered posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to adapt the decisions of the municipality to the interests of the mafia group Piromalli.
The accusations by the Anti-Mafia authorities of Calabria against Mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in Mafia business, are serious.
Gioacchino Piromalli, the older mediator between the clan and the public administration, and his nephew: the lawyer who bears the same name as the boss of the clan, had already been convicted of involvement in criminal associations of the mafia, at that time for a sum of 10 million euros.
"Despite any kind of moral and legal norm," the lawyers wrote, "the two local authorities had decided to pay the lawyer Piromalli money for consulting activities."
"This made it possible for the Mafia Group – the judges – to enter the town halls on an official basis and to take part in public administration policy."
The president of the Calabria Regional Committee, Agazio Loiero, does not deny that in his region "it is all but an exception to encounter links between local administrations and organised crime." "There are places where the concentration of the mafia is greater than in others in which such connections are practically unavoidable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who get a white vest."
The arrests of this morning follow those of last July, with which, according to the police, the Clan Piromalli was beheaded.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but already in 1991 – and also at that time because of alleged links between organized crime and local administration – local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, was elected head of the Middle Right Coalition after the May 2006 election.
He shouted scandal when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the council.
He was interested in this in the Deputy Minister, Marco Minniti, who accused him of inventing everything for political and strategic reasons. However, in connection with this morning’s arrest warrant, the judges stated that the Piromalli clan had even dared to request a change to the A3 project.
From a hearing in connection with the investigations on the Dal Torrione case, the willingness to meet the wishes of an entrepreneur, who is known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli – making public administration actions identical to the interests of this clan."
When the energy comes out of the waves, the great ones suddenly run up
It is a non-degrading source of money that covers over 70% of the surface of the planet and only now does this seem to understand the great energy companies of the world.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now looking for and also seeking to occupy, such as giants as Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; these studies have not been considerably intensified since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil broke down around 1980, the idea of marine energy was forgotten, but now the environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of global energy needs could be met by ocean waves.
This would be equal to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
There are also currents and tides.
Giants in the attack.
The first company that now relies on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are focusing on marine energy production.
"Chevron investigates these technologies" – according to the speaker of a company known to the U.S. giant in the Wall Street Journal – and considers the possibility of working with us."
It is a question of obtaining approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off Alaska's coast.
This is not an underestimated sign, especially when we consider that oil is still being promoted by the United States in Alaska, and President Bush just launched the plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers are talking about an increasing interest.
Even better technologies.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still emerging, not least because the last doubts have not yet been clarified by the environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with much greater environmental impact are needed.
There are various possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which move the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the float via pistons and cylinders.
This one drives a turbine, which in turn runs a generator.
The current is then sent via underwater pipelines to the coast.
Until now, there are four planned installations of this kind, which are only waiting for the state approval. Part of the energy generated could also be used for military facilities.
However, Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and a parking lot using underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Research, a particular interest deserves the potential that is present in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also the waves, and therefore a more reliable source of power.
Especially tidal energy is what led states like New York, Maine and Alaska as well as other coastal states to invest $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are planned for 2009.
